{"id":14880749,"mediaExerciseId":"19ee8364-760b-489b-ac16-d492be8a4a08","exerciseName":"10","chapterName":"2","chapterTitle":"Financial Statements, Taxes, and Cash Flow","groupId":612264,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":42,"solutions":[{"id":5910438,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to determine the basis of the conclusion.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/20/753854b9ebbe58bbd74b8433317cb6f4/76439c509d987bd146380dc6008f3e7e/lateximg_large.png","width":867},"regular":{"height":15,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/20/753854b9ebbe58bbd74b8433317cb6f4/76439c509d987bd146380dc6008f3e7e/lateximg.png","width":434}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The adjustments made by the company were mostly accounting changes. They had no effect on the cash flow or the market value of the company. However, if stockholders revalued derivatives as a result of the new accounting information, it would affect cash flow and market value.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/20/753854b9ebbe58bbd74b8433317cb6f4/68801457c8e62a68dd55ea641dd9cd05/lateximg_large.png","width":1004},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/20/753854b9ebbe58bbd74b8433317cb6f4/68801457c8e62a68dd55ea641dd9cd05/lateximg.png","width":502}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"dfba490f-4933-40b6-8b23-ee1de30309db","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2},{"id":5977381,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise will explain why the book concluded that even Procter & Gamble's operations resulted in a loss in 2019, the shareholders remain probably unaffected.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The emergence of the COVID-19 pandemic adversely affected many businesses as it led to millions of losses due to lower revenues generated and higher costs of operations. For instance, Procter & Gamble lost $8 million from writing off its Gillette brand.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"However, as discussed in the book, despite the losses incurred from brand deterioration, there are low chances that the entity's shareholders will lose money. The expense recorded by P&G d**oes not directly affect the cash flows** flowing in the entity.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"The decrease in value of the Gillette brand applies the **cash and accrual basis of accounting**. Such expense does not require any cash payment, producing no effects on the entity's cash balance. Although $8 billion will appear as an expense in the income statement, no money is involved means that cash value will remain the same.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"Despite the losses incurred by Procter & Gamble, the entity still have enough cash balance to suffice its operations. Income and cash are two different things but must be interdependently considered in making business decisions.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"e6f1fa5e-b3ba-4d4e-93eb-26f69cd77829","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionO